The intent of this rule isn't to ban in-place dunder methods from returning things other than `Self`. It's to catch a common error in stub files where these methods are annotated incorrectly: they nearly always return `self` at runtime, so they should therefore nearly always be annotated with `Self` in stub files.

I think the issue here is that flake8-pyi only supports stub files (and likely only ever will), whereas Ruff's adapted version of the rule also runs on `.py` files. For `.pyi` files, the heuristic makes sense IMO because these in-place dunders really do almost always return `self` at runtime, and in a stub file you haven't really got any other information to go on. I'm not sure this part of `PYI034` really makes sense at all in a `.py` file, however (not the way it's currently written, at least). In a `.py` file, a type checker will quickly tell you off if you write a method like this:

```py
class A:
    def __iadd__(self) -> int:
        return self
```

so in a `.py` file, I think it's probably only useful to emit this diagnostic if the return type references the enclosing class, like with the other parts of PYI034 -- i.e., restrict the rule to complaining about things like this:

```py
class A:
    def __iadd__(self) -> A:
        return self
```

